The paper deals with planar graphs and their drawings, which are typically studied in computational geometry (cs.CG). The algorithmic nature of the paper suggests that it could also belong to the data structures (cs.DS) or graph theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. The paper also involves some combinatorial aspects, such as the number of steps required for the morph, which could place it in the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the practical applications of the results, such as in visualization, which could make it relevant to the social and information sciences (cs.SI) sub-category.
